Derek Atkins (warlord@MIT.EDU) wrote:
:    MIKEINGLE@delphi.com (Mike Ingle) writes:
:    >Applied Cryptography on page 287 claims that low values of the public
:    >exponent E make RSA insecure. How small is too small? PGP usually uses
:    >E=17. Is this large enough?
: He wasn't asking about key-size.  He was asking about the value of 'e',
: the public exponent.

: Actually, this vulnerablility is only in pure RSA.  None of the public
: key programs (PGP, PEM, RIPEM, etc) use pure RSA.  Instead, they have
: a packet format inside the RSA block which causes a loss of
: multiplicitivity, and this, in turn, breaks the vulnerability.

Just for the record, RIPEM uses E=65537.

Mark R
